; Boot the whole kernel with a root filesystem attached, into USER MODE -- tasks 20 and 22.
;
; Every other test in this directory links a handful of kernel objects against a forged
; environment and drives one component.  This one links nothing: it loads the real `unix'
; image (built one directory up by kernel/CMakeLists.txt) with the same root2048.disk that
; fstest reads, and lets main() run the actual boot -- startup(), intrinit(), binit(),
; iinit(), iget() of the root, newproc() -- and then lets process 1 leave the kernel.
;
; WHAT REACHING `spin' PROVES.  It is the icode's failure loop (kernel/besm6.S), and to get
; there process 1 has to have gone the whole way:
;   * main() returned, so iinit() did not panic -- bread(rootdev, SUPERB) completed without
;     B_ERROR (else panic "iinit"), sbcheck() accepted the superblock (else panic "no root
;     fs"), and iget(rootdev, ROOTINO) read the root inode.  That is task 20's "done when",
;     and this test is still the regression guard for the b_un.b_addr fat-pointer fix (before
;     it, sbcheck() mis-read s_bsize and panicked, stopping in panic()'s own `stop' loop);
;   * _start's second half forged a user context and left through `выпр', so РП really maps
;     the image copyout() wrote and the machine really entered user mode;
;   * the icode executed out of that copy, so copyout() put the words where РП says they are;
;   * `$77 SYS_exec' vectored to 0577, the gate framed the machine, syscall() marshalled the
;     arguments and exec() ran namei() over a user-space `char *' -- the first system call
;     this kernel has ever taken from real user code;
;   * and it came back through the frame, since the icode is executing at all.
;
; ACC and r14 say WHICH way it came back.  There is no /etc/init on the image -- the userland
; is task 24 -- so the expected outcome is the failure one: ACC = -1 (an int is 41 bits, so
; that is 41 ones) and r14 = ENOENT (2), the errno-in-r14 convention (include/sys/reg.h;
; there is no carry bit on this machine).  BEWARE THE REGISTER NAMES: SIMH numbers index
; registers in OCTAL, so r14 is `M16' and r15 is `M17'.
;
; WHEN /etc/init APPEARS (task 24) THIS TEST CHANGES MEANING: a successful exec never returns
; to the icode, so `spin' is never reached and the breakpoint below never fires.  Rewrite it
; then to assert on init instead; do not just raise the step count.
;
; `break', so the run stops the instant PC reaches the loop.  Without it the step budget would
; expire wherever the clock happened to leave the machine -- often inside the timer interrupt,
; a few instructions from `spin' but not at it.
;
; `step', not `go': a hang must fail the run instead of hanging it -- `go' has no step bound.
;
; `set mmu cache' is new with task 22: the boot now programs РП (estabur -> sureg) and writes
; user memory through the map (copyout), so the БРЗ write-back is worth modelling here.
;
; WHAT THIS TEST DOES NOT CHECK: main()'s drainbrz() after the copyout.  Deleting it leaves
; this test passing, because main()'s epilogue and _start's tail happen to issue enough kernel
; stores to evict the icode's lines by age before the выпр.  The drain is not decoration --
; breaking on the instruction after the copyout shows seven of the nine words still in
; BRZ0-BRZ7 with memory reading zero -- but that measurement is written up at the call site in
; main.c, and this test cannot see it.  Do not read a PASS here as a verdict on the drain.
;
; `attach -r', and emphatically NOT `-n' (the trap TODO.md warns about): -r because the image
; is a build artifact, and no -n because `attach -n' CREATES AND FORMATS an empty container,
; on which sbcheck() would fail and the boot would panic.
;
; The console is deliberately NOT attached: the kernel's printf output has no reader here -- so
; execerr()'s `exec init: error 2' (sys1.c) goes nowhere in this run, and the assertions below
; are on the registers instead.  `make run' (kernel/unix.ini) is where you watch a boot.  @SPIN@ is pulled from unix.nm by
; genboot.cmake at build time -- it is a LINKED address that moves as the kernel grows, which
; is why this file is generated rather than hardcoded.

reset
set cpu latin
set mmu cache

load ../unix
attach -r md00 root2048.disk
break @SPIN@
step 50000000

if (PC != @SPIN@) echof "FAIL: boot did not reach the icode's failure loop (spin=@SPIN@). A PC in panic()'s stop loop means iinit() panicked (no root fs / iinit) -- e.g. the b_un.b_addr fat-pointer fix was reverted; a PC in the kernel means process 1 never left it, and if the step count ran out it hung, in idle() if the exec slept and never woke. Look the PC up in unix.nm. PC:"; ex PC; exit 1
if (ACC != 037777777777777) echof "FAIL: boot reached the icode, but exec did not report failure in ACC (expected -1, i.e. 41 ones). ACC:"; ex ACC; exit 1
if (M16 != 2) echof "FAIL: boot reached the icode, but r14 (SIMH M16) is not ENOENT -- exec failed somewhere other than namei(). r14:"; ex M16; exit 1

echof "PASS: boot -- the kernel mounted the root, entered user mode at the icode, took $77 exec from user code, and reported ENOENT for the missing /etc/init"
quit
